Yes, in LaTeX, you can specify subsections of subsections using the `\subsubsection` command. Here is an example showing how to use `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection`:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\section{Main Section}
This is the main section.

\subsection{Subsection}
This is a subsection.

\subsubsection{Subsubsection}
This is a subsubsection.

\end{document}
```

In this example, `\section` creates a main section, `\subsection` creates a subsection within the main section, and `\subsubsection` creates a subsection within the subsection. You can continue to nest sections further, but `\subsubsection` is typically the deepest level of sectioning provided by standard LaTeX classes.

Yes, you can structure your LaTeX document to have two columns per page by using the `twocolumn` option in the document class or by using the `multicol` package. Here are two ways to do it:

### Using the `twocolumn` Option in the Document Class

```latex
\documentclass[twocolumn]{article}

\begin{document}

\section{Main Section}
This is the main section in two-column format.

\subsection{Subsection}
This is a subsection in two-column format.

\subsubsection{Subsubsection}
This is a subsubsection in two-column format.

\end{document}
```

### Using the `multicol` Package

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{multicol}

\begin{document}

\begin{multicols}{2}

\section{Main Section}
This is the main section in two-column format.

\subsection{Subsection}
This is a subsection in two-column format.

\subsubsection{Subsubsection}
This is a subsubsection in two-column format.

\end{multicols}

\end{document}
```

In the first method, adding the `twocolumn` option to the document class makes the entire document use a two-column layout. In the second method, the `multicol` package allows you to specify a block of text to be in multiple columns by using the `multicols` environment, which gives you more flexibility if you want only parts of the document to be in multiple columns.
